Start working on a Jira issue by setting it to "In Progress" and creating a feature branch.

The start command will:
1. Set the issue status to "In Progress" in Jira
2. Create a new branch based on the issue key and summary
3. Switch to the newly created branch

If no issue ID is provided, you will be presented with a list of your open issues to choose from.

You can also create a new issue on the fly using the --title and --project flags.

Examples:
  # Start working on an existing issue
  fotingo start PROJ-123

  # Select from your open issues interactively
  fotingo start

  # Create a new issue and start working on it
  fotingo start -t "Fix login bug" -p PROJ -k Bug

  # Create a sub-task under a parent issue
  fotingo start -t "Implement feature" -p PROJ -a PROJ-100

  # Start an issue without creating a branch (just set status)
  fotingo start PROJ-123 --no-branch

  # Start in a new sibling worktree
  fotingo start PROJ-123 --worktree

  # Start with labels on a new issue
  fotingo start -t "New feature" -p PROJ -l frontend -l priority

Usage:
  fotingo start [issueId] [flags]

Flags:
  -d, --description string     Description for new issue
  -e, --epic string            Epic issue to link the created issue to
  -h, --help                   help for start
  -i, --interactive            Interactively create a new issue before starting work
  -k, --kind string            Issue type: Story, Bug, Task (default: Task) (default "Task")
  -l, --labels strings         Labels to add to created issue
  -n, --no-branch              Set issue to In Progress without creating/switching branch
  -a, --parent string          Parent issue for sub-tasks
  -p, --project string         Project key for new issue (required with --title)
  -t, --title string           Create new issue with this title
      --worktree               Create the issue branch in a new sibling linked worktree
      --worktree-path string   Parent directory for the created linked worktree

Global Flags:
  -b, --branch string   Base branch override (default: auto-detect)
      --debug           Show diagnostic output (includes verbose)
      --json            Output results as JSON
      --no-color        Disable colored output
      --quiet           Suppress non-essential output
  -v, --verbose         Show step-level progress output
  -y, --yes             Accept defaults without prompting
